In this tutorial, we will analyze the classical assumptions of linear regression.

What makes OLS BLUE

Classical assumptions of linear regression

  1. The dependent variable is linearly related to the coefficients of the model and the model is correctly specified. \[{y_i} = {\beta _1} + {\beta _2}{x_{i2}} + \cdots + {\beta _K}{x_{iK}} + {e_i},\;\;i = 1, \ldots ,N\]

  2. No perfect multicollinearity. No independent variable has a perfect linear relationship with any of the other independent variables.

  3. The mean of the error term is zero.\[E({y_i}) = {\beta _1} + {\beta _2}{x_{i2}} + \cdots + {\beta _K}{x_{iK}} \Leftrightarrow E({e_i}) = 0\]

  4. The error term has a constant variance. No heteroscedasticity.\[{\mathop{\rm var}} ({y_i}) = {\mathop{\rm var}} ({e_i}) = {\sigma ^2}\]

  5. The error term is normally distributed. (Not absolutely necessary)\[{y_i}~N\left[ {({\beta _1} + {\beta _2}{x_{i2}} + \cdots + {\beta _K}{x_{iK}}),\;{\sigma ^2}} \right] \Leftrightarrow {e_i}~N(0,{\sigma ^2})\]

  6. The error terms are uncorrelated with each other. No autocorrelation or serial correlation. \[{\mathop{\rm cov}} ({y_i},{y_j}) = {\mathop{\rm cov}} ({e_i},{e_j}) = 0\]

  7. The independent variable(s) is/are uncorrelated with the equation error term.

Two assumptions about the explanatory variables

  1. The explanatory variables are not random variables
    • We are assuming that the values of the explanatory variables are known to us prior to our observing the values of the dependent variable
  2. Any one of the explanatory variables is not an exact linear function of the others (More on this latter)
    • This assumption is equivalent to assuming that no variable is redundant
    • If this assumption is violated, then \(x'x\) is less than full rank and thus it is not inevitable.

Big Andys Hamburger Sales

Data

library(POE5Rdata)
data(andy)
datatable(head(andy))

The basic andy model

mod1 <- lm(sales~price+advert, data=andy)
(smod1 <- summ(mod1))

Dependent variable sales
Type OLS linear regression

The quadratic andy model

mod2 <- lm(sales~price+advert+I(advert^2), data=andy)
(smod2 <- summ(mod2))
